01:07:23.160 --> 01:07:24.360
AUDIENCE: Is the problem
with cybersecurity

01:07:24.360 --> 01:07:26.610
that nobody wants to deal with
it, or everybody wants to?

01:07:26.610 --> 01:07:28.120
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Everybody
wants to deal with it.

01:07:28.120 --> 01:07:28.620
Yeah.

01:07:32.040 --> 01:07:35.190
The problem is that the
Department of Homeland Security

01:07:35.190 --> 01:07:37.290
has no expertise
in power systems.

01:07:37.290 --> 01:07:42.030
And the Department of Energy has
no expertise in cybersecurity.

01:07:42.030 --> 01:07:45.600
So whoever gets it
has to staff up.

01:07:45.600 --> 01:07:48.690
Well, staffing up is fun.

01:07:48.690 --> 01:07:49.500
You add headcounts.

01:07:49.500 --> 01:07:50.125
You add people.

01:07:50.125 --> 01:07:51.360
You add payroll.

01:07:51.360 --> 01:07:52.890
You add prestige.

01:07:52.890 --> 01:07:56.880
So whoever does it
gets to staff up.

01:07:56.880 --> 01:08:01.440
If you split it, then you've
got sort of dueling staffs.

01:08:01.440 --> 01:08:03.610
You don't understand
anything about electricity.

01:08:03.610 --> 01:08:04.110
Oh, yeah.

01:08:04.110 --> 01:08:05.850
But you don't understand
about security.

01:08:05.850 --> 01:08:07.630
I mean, come on.

01:08:07.630 --> 01:08:08.760
That doesn't work.

01:08:08.760 --> 01:08:14.370
So everybody wants--
well, both people want it.

01:08:14.370 --> 01:08:16.859
And at some point, I
assume, one of them

01:08:16.859 --> 01:08:20.189
will be declared the
winner, but not soon.

